04269nam a22007575i 9789048516803DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485168037 a10.1515/97890485168032doi  a(DE-B1597)502561  a(OCoLC)803370024  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aQC16.G6bL948 2012 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a199.4921 aLüthy, Christoph, eauthor.10aDavid Gorlæus (1591-1612) :bAn Enigmatic Figure in the History of Philosophy and Science /cChristoph Lüthy. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory of Science and Scholarship in the Netherlands ;v1300tFrontmatter -- tTable Of Contents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introducing Gorlæus -- tChapter 2. Gorlæus' Two Treatises -- tChapter 3. Gorlæus' Life -- tChapter 4. Gorlæus' Place In The History Of Seventeenth-Century Thought -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen David Gorlæus, a prospective theology student, passed away tragically at twenty-one years old, he left behind two highly innovative manuscripts, which were published posthumously in 1620 and 1651, respectively. As his identity was unknown, seventeenth-century readers understood him both as an anti-Aristotelian thinker and a precursor of Descartes. In contrast, by the twentieth century, historians depicted him as an atomist, natural scientist, and even a chemist. David Gorlæus (1591-1612) seeks to pull together what is known of this enigmatic figure. Combining multiple historical sources, Christoph Lüthy provides a narrative of Gorlæus's life that casts light on his exceptional body of work and places it firmly at the intersection between philosophy, the nascent natural sciences, and theology.   "Christoph Lüthy is the first to tell the complete story of David Gorlæus and to reconstruct his image on the basis of all remaining sources. Showing in a convincing way that Gorlæus is one of the key figures in the renewal of atomistic philosophy in the seventeenth century and a major influence on many philosophers that are much better known, he leaves us with the melancholy picture of someone who died too young to become one of the heroes of the scientific revolution."-Theo Verbeek, Utrecht University   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aAtomism. 0aPhilosopherszNetherlands. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2002-2015z978311066278808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam Univ.Press  eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048516803zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048516803.jpg  a978-3-11-060651-5  Amsterdam Univ.Press  eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2002-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG